For a nonlinear ODE system ẋ = f(x) with equilibrium at x = 0, the Lyapunov direct method proves stability by constructing a Lyapunov function V(x) that is positive definite and satisfies V̇(x) = ∇V·f(x) ≤ 0 in a neighborhood of the origin. If V̇(x) < 0 for all x ≠ 0 nearby, the equilibrium is asymptotically stable; if only V̇(x) ≤ 0, it's stable. Common choices for V(x) include quadratic forms V(x) = xᵀPx for matrices P ≻ 0 or higher-order polynomials. Verify positive definiteness via eigenvalue analysis or Sylvester criterion. The basin of attraction is characterized by the sublevel set {x : V(x) ≤ c} for the largest c where V̇ ≤ 0 holds. No solution trajectories need explicit computation—stability follows purely from the existence of a suitable V(x).